Certainly! In LaTeX, you can use the `tableofcontents` command to generate a table of contents for your document. The basic syntax of the command is:
\begin{code}
\tableofcontents
\end{code}

This will generate a table of contents that includes the section headings in your document, along with their corresponding page numbers.
Here is an example of how you can use the `tableofcontents` command in a LaTeX document:
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\section{Introduction}
\section{Methodology}
\section{Results}
\section{Conclusion}

\tableofcontents

\end{document}

In this example, the `section` command is used to create three section headings in the document. The `tableofcontents` command is then used to generate a table of contents that includes the section headings and their corresponding page numbers.
To customize the appearance of the table of contents, you can use various options and commands provided by LaTeX. For example, you can use the `title` option to set the title of the table of contents, the `font` option to set the font used for the table of contents, and the `format` option to set the format of the table of contents (e.g., to use a numbered or unnumbered table of contents).
Here is an example of how you can use the `tableofcontents` command with some of these options:
\documentclass{article}

\begin{document}

\section{Introduction}
\section{Methodology}
\section{Results}
\section{Conclusion}

\tableofcontents

\title{My Document}
\font{times}
\format{numbered}

\end{document}

In this example, the `title` option is used to set the title of the table of contents to "My Document". The `font` option is used to set the font used for the table of contents to "times". The `format` option is used to set the format of the table of contents to "numbered", which will generate a numbered table of contents.
I hope this helps! Let me know if you have any questions.
